Description
Performs a complete, structured analysis of any CV/resume and provides detailed, actionable feedback. Use this skill whenever the user uploads or pastes a CV, mentions they want to improve their resume, prepare for a job application, or asks "what's wrong with my CV", "review my resume", "CV feedback", "resume check", "optimize my CV", or anything related to evaluating or improving a CV or resume. Covers: personal profile/intro, negative words, temporal and conceptual inconsistencies, multiple degrees, published works, application opportunities, structure/format, and ATS optimization.CV Analyzer Skill
Analyze the CV thoroughly and deliver a structured report across 8 sections. Be direct, constructive, and specific — never generic. Always quote actual text from the CV when flagging issues. Respond in the same language the user is writing in (even if the CV itself is in a different language).

Step 0 — Obtain the CV
If the user hasn't already provided the CV:

Ask them to paste the CV text OR upload the file (PDF/DOCX)
Ask which position or field they are targeting — this is essential for the education and opportunities sections
If they don't know the exact role, ask for the domain at minimum (e.g. IT, marketing, research, finance)


Report Structure
Present results in this order with clear headings. Use ✅ / ⚠️ / ❌ to indicate severity.

SECTION 1 — Personal Profile / Intro Summary
Check whether a profile/summary/about me section exists:

Missing entirely → ❌ Explain why it matters (recruiters spend ~6 seconds on first scan) and provide a personalized draft template based on the rest of the CV
Exists but weak → ⚠️ Show what's missing: concrete achievements, domain keywords, appropriate tone
Exists and strong → ✅ Acknowledge what works and suggest any minor improvements

After analyzing all other sections, return here and offer specific, personalized suggestions for the intro based on what you discovered — e.g. if they have relevant publications, suggest mentioning them; if there's a career pivot, suggest addressing it explicitly.

SECTION 2 — Negative, Weak, or Damaging Words and Phrases
Scan the full CV text. Quote the exact word or phrase found, explain why it's problematic, and provide a concrete alternative.
Categories to check:
Empty buzzwords (claim nothing, prove nothing):

hardworking, team player, go-getter, passionate, detail-oriented, people person, self-motivated, dynamic, results-driven, synergy, think outside the box, proactive, dedicated, innovative, strategic thinker

Passive verbs that dilute impact:

"responsible for", "helped with", "assisted in", "worked on", "involved in", "participated in", "contributed to"
→ Replace with strong action verbs: Led, Built, Delivered, Designed, Reduced, Increased, Managed, Launched, Drove, Spearheaded, Owned

Phrases that signal weakness or failure:

"tried to", "attempted to", "familiar with" (instead of actual skill level), "some experience in", "basic knowledge of", "exposure to"

Unjustified superlatives:

"best", "world-class", "expert" (without evidence), "guru", "ninja", "rockstar", "unicorn"

Words that must never appear in a CV:

fired, let go, laid off, failed, problems, weaknesses, terminated, quit
Use of "I" at the start of bullet points (CVs are written in implied first person, no pronoun)
Age, religion, ethnicity, marital status (in countries where not required)

Reporting format:

⚠️ "responsible for managing a team" → Replace with: "Managed a cross-functional team of X, delivering Y outcome on time and under budget"


SECTION 3 — Temporal and Conceptual Inconsistencies
3a. Timeline Checks
Build a mental timeline and verify:

Impossible overlaps: Two full-time jobs in the same period without mentioning part-time/freelance/consulting status
Experience vs. estimated age: If you can estimate graduation year, check whether claimed years of experience are mathematically possible
Unexplained gaps >1 year: Flag and suggest the person address them (e.g. caregiving, personal projects, education, health, travel)
Declared experience exceeds time available: e.g. graduated 2018 but claims "10 years of experience" in 2024

3b. Conceptual Anachronism Checks (technologies / fields that are too new)
Compare claimed years of experience against when the technology actually became commercially available:
Technology / ConceptAvailable at commercial scale sinceAI Agents / Agentic AI2023ChatGPT / LLM prompting2022Stable Diffusion / Generative Image AI2022GPT-4 level APIs2023RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)2023Vector databases (commercial)2021Kubernetes (mainstream)2016React (popular)2015Blockchain / Web3 commercial2017Cloud-native (AWS/GCP mainstream)2014
→ See references/tech-timeline.md for the full extended list
If someone claims "8 years of AI Agents experience" in 2025 → ❌ Impossible; the technology is ~2 years old. Explain clearly and suggest a corrected phrasing, e.g.: "Consider rephrasing as '3 years of LLM/AI Agents experience, 8 years of broader software engineering'"
Be nuanced: A researcher may have worked with a technology before its commercial adoption — if the CV shows academic publications or research roles, apply more flexibility.

SECTION 4 — Multiple Degrees / Academic Inconsistencies
If the CV contains two or more degrees/institutions:

Identify the field of each (e.g. Mechanical Engineering + Digital Marketing)
Compare against the target job provided by the user
Recommend which to list first and how to frame it
If the degrees are unrelated to each other:

⚠️ Suggest adding a sentence in the intro that explains the non-linear path
Propose a positive angle: "T-shaped professional", "interdisciplinary background", "cross-functional expertise"


If one degree is completely irrelevant to the target role:

⚠️ Suggest either removing it or listing it minimally (name, institution, year — no further detail)


SECTION 5 — Published Works / Research
If the CV lists published papers, articles, or research:
Step 1: Analyze each title:

Is it relevant to the target role? ✅ / ⚠️ / ❌
Is the title descriptive and clear, or vague and ambiguous?

Step 2: If the title is inconclusive OR appears irrelevant to the job:

Search for the paper online (Google Scholar, ResearchGate, PubMed, Semantic Scholar) using the exact title
Read the abstract if publicly available
Assess actual relevance based on content

Step 3: If the paper cannot be found online and the title is inconclusive:

Ask the user to provide the abstract
Explain why: "I wasn't able to find this paper online and the title doesn't clearly indicate relevance to [target role]. Could you share the abstract so I can complete the analysis?"

Step 4: Report findings:

Relevant works → how to feature them more prominently in the CV
Irrelevant works → whether to keep, remove, or move to a separate "Publications" appendix section


SECTION 6 — Application Opportunities / Alternative Job Titles
Based on the full CV (skills, experience, education, publications), identify:

Current declared title — is it the best fit for what they're targeting? Are there more marketable variants?
Alternative positions the CV already qualifies them for (that they may not have considered):

Minimum 5 concrete job titles
Brief explanation of why the CV supports each


Aspirational positions (1–2 additional skills away):

2–3 roles they could reach with targeted upskilling
Specify exactly what's missing for each


Alternative industries/sectors where the profile is valuable (e.g. a software engineer with healthcare experience → healthtech, medtech, hospital IT, health insurance tech)


SECTION 7 — Structure, Format, and Essential Information
7a. Essential Contact Details
Check for presence and quality of:

 Full name
 Email address (professional — flag unprofessional usernames)
 Phone number (with international dialing code if applying internationally)
 LinkedIn URL (customized, not the auto-generated one)
 Location (city + country is sufficient; full street address is unnecessary and a privacy risk)
 GitHub / Portfolio link (for technical or creative roles)
 Desired work arrangement (full-time/part-time/remote/hybrid) — optional but useful

7b. Length and Density

1 page: Ideal for <5 years of experience
2 pages: Acceptable for 5–15 years
3+ pages: ❌ Too long for a standard CV (exception: academic CVs)
Flag redundant content or unnecessary detail (e.g. generic daily responsibilities, jobs from 20 years ago with no relevance)

7c. Format and Readability

Mixed fonts or hard-to-read typefaces → ❌
Complex tables or multi-column layouts → ⚠️ (ATS parsing issues)
Missing month+year on job dates → ⚠️
Dense paragraphs instead of bullet points → ⚠️ (bullet points preferred)
Reverse chronological order → ✅ Standard; any other order → flag and explain the risk

7d. Achievements vs. Responsibilities

Does the CV describe what they did or what they achieved?
Check for concrete metrics: "Increased sales by 30%", "Managed team of 8", "Reduced infrastructure costs by $50K/year"
If metrics are absent → ⚠️ Suggest adding them wherever plausible, and offer prompting questions to help the person recall numbers (e.g. "How large was the team you managed?", "What was the revenue impact?")


SECTION 8 — ATS Optimization (Applicant Tracking Systems)
ATS software scans CVs automatically before a human recruiter ever sees them. Many CVs are rejected at this stage due to formatting or keyword issues.
8a. ATS Parsing Problems

❌ Important information in headers/footers (ATS often skips these entirely)
❌ Multi-column layouts or tables (ATS reads them out of order)
❌ Images, icons, graphs, charts (ATS ignores all visual elements)
❌ Non-standard fonts or image-based PDFs (text not scannable)
❌ .pages or other non-standard formats → Recommend .docx or clean PDF
⚠️ Abbreviations without the full form (e.g. "PM" → write "Project Manager (PM)")

8b. Keywords and Density

Identify 5–10 essential keywords for the CV's target domain
Check whether they appear in the CV — ideally in the top two-thirds of the document
Suggest adding missing keywords in natural context (not forced)
⚠️ Keyword stuffing (excessive repetition) → penalized by modern ATS platforms

8c. Standard Section Headings
ATS systems recognize standard headings. Flag unusual ones:

✅ Experience / Work Experience / Professional Experience
✅ Education / Academic Background
✅ Skills / Technical Skills / Core Competencies
✅ Certifications / Licenses
❌ "My Journey", "Where I've Been", "Things I Know", "My Story" → ATS won't categorize these correctly

8d. Date Formats

✅ "Jan 2020 – Mar 2023" or "01/2020 – 03/2023"
❌ "Early 2020", "Recently", "2020-ish", "A few years ago" → ATS cannot parse these


Final Summary and Prioritization
Close the report with an estimated overall score (1–10) and a Top 3 Immediate Actions list — the highest-impact changes the person can make right now.
Format:
📊 Overall Score: X/10

🎯 Top 3 Immediate Actions:
1. [Most impactful action]
2. [Second most impactful]
3. [Third most impactful]

Model Instructions

Never be generic. Always quote actual text from the CV when flagging an issue.
Don't invent problems. If a section is genuinely good, say so clearly.
Always pair every problem with a solution. Never flag without offering an alternative or fix.
If the CV is incomplete (e.g. user pasted only part of it), state what's missing before proceeding.
Response language = the language the user is writing in, regardless of the CV's language.
Tone: Be like a sharp, experienced career coach — honest, direct, but always constructive and encouraging.
